- fnmatch-p-hang: tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst hangs the testee at 100%
  CPU; not yet isolated to a specific case within the file.

    ./shish tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst

- fdtable-cycle-detection: the fdtable resolver has no real cycle
  detection, only a defensive depth cap; a genuinely cyclic
  redirection fails instead of resolving. Not yet isolated to a
  concrete repro; illustrative (unconfirmed) attempt:

    exec 3<&0
    exec 4<&3
    exec 3<&4

- sig-push-sigset-cast: sig_push() reinterprets sigset_t through an
  unsigned long*, UB on any ABI where sizeof(sigset_t) differs;
  currently harmless because the function is unused (dead code, not
  reachable from any shell script).

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe. Any background job
  finishing exercises the handler, though the unsafety is a latent
  race, not a deterministic per-run failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

- glob-not-triggered-for-plain-arguments: filename globbing
  ("*"/"?"/"["/"]" in an ordinary, unquoted command argument) never
  actually runs glob(3) for a plain top-level argument -- confirmed
  with a debugger: parse_unquoted.c sets S_GLOB on the parsed
  N_ARGSTR node for other glob-special-char cases (e.g. the "["/"]"
  the test builtin's own name is made of, or a stray one inside an
  escape-sequence-like string), but NOT for an ordinary wildcard
  pattern like "*.txt" as a bare command argument -- expand_arg.c's
  own "subarg->nargstr.flag & S_GLOB" check saw flag == 0 for it, so
  expand_glob() is never even called and the pattern is passed
  through completely unexpanded/literal. This was previously an
  unconfirmed suspicion in TODO.md ("glob check on subargs other than
  argstr") -- now confirmed and repro'd; not yet root-caused further
  (i.e. why S_GLOB ends up set for some glob-special-char words but
  not this one specifically hasn't been traced into parse_unquoted.c
  yet).

    mkdir -p /tmp/globtest && touch /tmp/globtest/a.txt /tmp/globtest/b.txt
    ./shish -c 'echo /tmp/globtest/*.txt'
    # prints the literal "/tmp/globtest/*.txt", not "a.txt b.txt"


